00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:12.920
Firstly some terminology stuff

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:15.060
because the phrases cart abandonment

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:17.440
and checkout abandonment are thrown around

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:18.830
kind of interchangeably.

00:02:18.830 --> 00:02:20.730
They actually do mean different things.

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:23.330
And by the way, for those
who aren't in the UK,

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:27.810
basket or basket if you're
up north means cart.

00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:30.460
So cart abandonment
and basket abandonment,

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:32.310
they mean exactly the same thing.

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:34.600
Right, if it's not already
complicated enough,

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:36.160
when you go onto an eCommerce store

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:39.060
and you put a product in
your basket or your cart,

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:40.880
but you then don't checkout

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:43.700
that is called cart abandonment.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:45.730
You've got your cart,
but you've abandoned it,

00:02:45.730 --> 00:02:47.740
you haven't gone to the next stage.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:50.877
If you open that basket or
cart, then click checkout

00:02:50.877 --> 00:02:52.780
and you go into the checkout process

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:56.560
but you don't finish it,
that is checkout abandonment.

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:58.100
Now what we're gonna be looking at today

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.200
are ways of mitigating
both of these things.

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:03.560
One of the most useful
places that you can go

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:06.370
to get insights on this
stuff is Google Analytics.

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:08.910
And if you go to conversions, eCommerce,

00:03:08.910 --> 00:03:11.520
shopping behaviour, you should see a chart

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:13.810
that looks something like this.

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:16.420
What this shows you is
the different stages

00:03:16.420 --> 00:03:17.920
of your eCommerce funnel.

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:19.300
For example, in this case,

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:21.670
we can see that there
have been 66,000 sessions

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:22.690
in this time period,

00:03:22.690 --> 00:03:25.540
with 21,000 of those sessions
having product views,

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:28.360
i.e. the person visited a product page,

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:32.320
3 1/2 thousand of those sessions
had an add to basket in,

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:34.920
2,800 of those sessions

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.660
had someone begin the checkout process

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:42.660
and 1,133 of them resulted in sales.

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:45.160
And what we can see is
the percentage drop off

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:46.610
at each stage.

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:49.490
Now the question that you
might have right now is

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:51.190
hmm, is my data normal?

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:52.900
My data looks different to this.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:55.530
And it's a very common question
that store owners have.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:59.430
What is an acceptable
checkout abandonment rate?

